{"title_page": "Dewesoft X Software", "text_new": "Dewesoft X is a software tool developed by Dewesoft d.o.o. with a primary focus on data recording and data analysis. It is an accompanying product to instruments from Dewesoft company. The latest version of the software is Dewesoft X3, released in October 2017.\n\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Dewesoft X\n| logo = <!-- Image name is enough. -->\n| logo alt = \n| logo caption = \n| screenshot = <!-- Image name is enough. -->\n| screenshot size =\n| screenshot alt = \n| caption = \n| collapsible = <!-- Any text here will collapse the screenshot. -->\n| author = \n| developer = Dewesoft d.o.o.\n| released = {{Start date and age|2001|df=yes}}\n| discontinued = <!-- Set to yes if software is discontinued, otherwise omit. -->\n| ver layout = <!-- simple (default) or stacked -->\n| latest release version = Dewesoft X3 SP11\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2020|03|df=yes}}\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| repo = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| programming language = Delphi, C++\n| engine = <!-- or engines -->\n| operating system = Windows 7 or later\n| platform = x86-64\n| included with = \n| size = \n| language = \n| language count = <!-- Number only -->\n| language footnote = \n| genre = \nData acquisition, instrument control, test automation, analysis and signal processing, industrial control\n| license = Proprietary\n| alexa = \n| website = {{URL|https://dewesoft.com/products/daq-software/dewesoft-x/}}\n| standard = \n| AsOf = \n}}\n\n== Version history ==\n\nThe first version of the software is Dewesoft 5.0, released in 2001 and patented in 2002 at the USA and EU patent office for the capability of synchronized presentation of all acquired and mathematically transformed signals on a personal computer (PC). \n\nIn 2003 Dewesoft 6.0 was released, adding essential features suited for automotive, telemetry and power measurements and power analysis.\n\nDewesoft 7.0 data acquisition software was launched in 2008 with a completely overhauled graphical user interface and new capabilities.\n\nThe company changed the software\u2019s naming convention with the release of Dewesoft X in 2012. With this version of the software, Dewesoft for the first time completely abandoned support for 3rd party analog DAQ hardware and exclusively supported Dewesoft DAQ hardware. It was also no longer commercially available but was instead given to customers free of charge as an application for acquired data acquisition hardware with lifetime free upgrades.\n\nDewesoft X2 was released in 2015 and brought significant performance improvements, with calculations being executed up to 4 times faster and graphics being drawn up to 10 times faster than in Dewesoft X, due to them being executed in parallel. \n\nIn 2017 Dewesoft X3 was officially launched with its main improvement being the availability in a 64-bit version. As of February 2019, Dewesoft X3 SP10 is the latest stable build of Dewesoft X3.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name-version!! Date\n|-\n| Dewesoft 5.0 || 2001\n|-\n| Dewesoft 6.0 || 2003\n|-\n| Dewesoft 7.0 || 2008\n|-\n| Dewesoft X || 2012\n|-\n| Dewesoft X2 || 2015\n|-\n| Dewesoft X3 || 2017\n|}\n\n=== Available versions ===\n\nDewesoft X3 is always available in three versions, release, release candidate and development as part of a branching strategy to clear as many bugs as possible before deploying the software in critical operations. \n\nThe release cycle usually lasts about 2 to 3 months, after which point the versions get shifted, the release candidate branch becomes the new release branch, the development branch becomes the new release candidate branch and a new development branch is created.\n\nThe roles of the branches are as follows:\n\n*Release: the release branch is the most recent stable release version which should be used for real measurements. The version itself does not change unless a critical issue is discovered in it, at which point a patch of the release branch is released. \n\n*Release candidate: the release candidate branch contains the fixes for bugs that have been discovered in the release branch, but are not critical to the measurement process. It is updated regularly and will sometimes also include minor features.\n\n*Development: all bug fixes from the release candidate branch are also applied to the development branch, which is mostly used for adding new features. This means that all new functionality passes through an approximately 4-month long release cycle that helps discover and remove issues before deployment.\n\n[[File:X3 screen.png| thumb |Sreenshot of Dewesoft X3]]\n\n== Functionality ==\n\nDewesoft\u2019s primary objective is to be a one software solution for all applications. The current scope of functionality covers a wide range of automotive, power analysis, NVH, aerospace, industrial and civil engineering applications. At the same time, the software needs to be as easy to use as possible, allowing users to set up and perform simple measurements in a short time.\n\nThe key that allows Dewesoft to execute both effectively is that it is channel based with a modular infrastructure. All data that comes into the software (via Dewesoft hardware or otherwise) becomes a Dewesoft channel and is treated as such. Channels have basic properties (name, color, unit), can be scaled, visualized, used in other modules (statistics, filters, FFT) or exported. \n\nThe modular infrastructure means that users only see the core applications of the software, while other, more application specific parts are hidden and can be added at any time. The modules usually get data using channel inputs and they produce new channels as results. For example, the Power analysis module takes voltage and current channel as inputs and produces the calculated power, energy and THD channels.\n\n=== General functionality ===\n\nThe functions described below are available to all users of Dewesoft hardware without additional licensing costs (see Licensing policy).\n\n==== Data recording ====\n\nDewesoft X software is unique in terms of supported interfaces. No other data acquisition software can match a number of supported interfaces that can be acquired fully synchronized, stored and visualized in the same data file. Supported interfaces include:\n\n*Analog data: IEPE/ICP, Charge, Strain, Stress, LVDT, Voltage, Current Resistance, Thermocouple, RTD\n*Digital, counter and encoder\n*Video DirectX video cameras, high-speed video cameras, IR thermal video cameras\n*Navigational GPS/GNSS and Inertial Navigation\n*Vehicle bus systems: CAN bus, OBDII on CAN, CAN FD, J1939 and J1587, XCP, CCP, LIN bus, FlexRay, Kistler KiRoad, MTS road simulator integration, Testbed AK-protocol support, *ETAS INCA over CAN, SENT (SAE J2716)\n*Aerospace interfaces: IRIG-108 CHAPTER 10, IRIG CHAPTER 4, ARINC 429, MIL-STD-1553\n*Industrial bus systems: Siemens S7, Modbus, OPC-UA, EtherCAT\n\n==== Mathematics ====\n\nDewesoft comes standard with a wide range of mathematical functions:\n\n*Formula\n*IIR filter\n*FIR filter\n*Frequency domain filter\n*Basic statistics\n*Array statistics\n*ClassificationTime reference curve\n*XY reference\n*Frequency domain reference curve\n*Vector reference\n*Integral derivative\n*Latch value math\n*Scope\n*Delay channel\n*Time-to-vector transformExact frequency\n*Correlation\n*Cepstrum\n*Full spectrum\n*Frequency integration and derivation\n*FFT\n*Short-time Fourier transform\n*Octave analysis\n*Angle sensor math\n*Envelope detection\n*Counting\n*Weighting filters\n*PID control\n*Strain rosette\n*PCB Strain rate\n*Vector matrix constant\n*Scaling\n\nAll of the above listed functions are modular and take inputs in the form of channels, simply by selecting them either from a drop-down menu or ticking a checkbox. This allows users to set up the same mathematical operations on a lot of channels very quickly, for example calculating the average value of every 5 seconds or applying an additional software FIR filter. In both cases, no programming or visual sequencing is required.\n\n==== Visualization ====\n\nVisualization of data in Dewesoft is done using so called graphical widgets, which users can drag and drop to the screen and arrange them in any way they choose. Each widget is different visually and it can only accept channels of certain types. For example, a digital meter can only display scalar channels while a 2D plot can only display array (vector or matrix) channels.\n\nDewesoft\u2019s library contains the following widgets:\n\n*Digital meter\n*Recorder\n*Vector scope\n*Horizontal/vertical bar graph\n*Vertical recorder\n*X-Y recorder\n*Video\n*Analog meter\n*Scope\n*Map\n*Indicator lamp\n*Overload indicator\n*2D graph\n*Tabular display\n*3D graph\n*Orbit plot\n*Control element\n*Discrete display\n*2D/3D Table\n\n==== Data analysis ====\n\nBecause Dewesoft is able to perform calculations during the recording of the data, this means that some sort of data analysis can already be performed online. A very useful feature to help with this is the so called \u201cFreeze mode\u201d, which allows users to look at all of the data that has already been recorded while the measurement is still in progress. \n\nIn offline analysis, Dewesoft displays the whole measurement timeline but allows users to use cursors on the recorder instrument (or the +- buttons) to zoom in to sections where they want to study the data more closely.\n\nDue to high sampling, users are often dealing with data files that have file sizes in the GB range. To enable smooth operation, Dewesoft stores data in layers (buffers), meaning that Dewesoft will not only store the raw data, but also Min/Max/Avg/Rms values for each channel at a few longer intervals. When opening data files, Dewesoft will only load display the most appropriate reduced buffer, therefore saving a lot of time not having to go through all of the data, allowing fast data loading times. If the user zooms deep within a section of the file, he will move through the different buffers and finally see the actual samples of each channel. \n\n==== Reporting ====\n\nAs Dewesoft is primarily a data acquisition software, it wants to allow users the flexibility of being able to analyze the data in other software. With that in mind, Dewesoft offers a variety of export formats compatible with popular analysis tools. Users are free to configure which channels they want to export and at which rates. When exporting to different rates from the ones that the data was stored with, Dewesoft has a resampling functionality to prevent aliasing.\n\nData can be exported to the following formats:\n\n*FlexPro [*.fpd]\n*Microsoft Excel [*.xls]\n*DIAdem [*.dat]\n*Matlab [*.mat]\n*Universal file format 58 [*.unv]\n*FAMOS [*.dat]\n*NSoft time series [*.dac]\n*Text File [*.txt]\n*Sony [*.log]\n*RPCIII [*.rsp]\n*Comtrade [*.cfg]\n*Technical data management [*.tdm]\n*JSON [*.json]\n*ASAM MDF4 [*.mf4]\n*S3 [*.s3t]\n*ATI [*.ati]\n*HDF5 [*.h5]\n*DynaWorks neutral file [*.nt]\n*Standard data file (SDF) [*.dat/sdf]\n*WFT [*.wft]\n*Replay [*.rpl]\n*Wave [*.wav]\n*Google earth [*.kml]\n*BWF [*.dat]\n\nTo create advanced reports, users can take advantage of using Dewesoft in combination with Excel or FlexPro templates, printing the measurement screen as a PDF or exporting it as a video file.\n\n==== Sequencing ====\n\nThe sequencer is a visual programming tool within Dewesoft that can be used for test automation. It is basically a block diagram where the users can drag & drop and connect blocks which perform certain actions, therefore constructing a sequence of events. In cases where measurements are done in a repetitive manner and perhaps require user interaction in a predetermined way, the sequencer is very handy. \n\nThe sequencer can load setup files, put Dewesoft in measure mode, store data, switch between displays, wait for values or user interaction, export data or print reports. It works in conjunction with setup files, which are still used to prepare the test configuration.\n\n=== Application specific functionality ===\n\nWhile Dewesoft\u2019s primary focus is data acquisition, the software is also very capable in data analysis. As not every user requires every analysis option, these modules are usually offered at an additional cost as sort of a convenience feature for not having to manually enter all of the calculations using the formula tool. For example Deweosoft power analysis module offers a convenient way of selecting voltage and current data and will produce results based on the user\u2019s wishes by ticking a few checkboxes. \n\nDewesot offers solutions in the following areas:\n\n==== Power/Energy analysis\t ====\n*Power Analyzer\n*Power Quality Analyzer\n*Wind & Solar testing\n*Electrical Grid & Power System testing\n*E-mobility\n==== Vehicle Testing\t ====\n*Road Load Data analysis\n*Durability test bed integration\n*Brake testing\n*Brake Noise testing\n*Polygon and GPS solutions\n*ADAS testing\n*Vehicle Dynamics\n*Combustion Analysis\n*Harsh Environment testing\n*Crash Test\n*Fatigue\n==== Vibration analysis\t ====\n*FFT analyser\n*Order tracking\n*Rotational and Torsional Vibrations\n*Balancing\n*Orbital Analysis\n*Shock Response Spectrum\n*Bearing Envelope detection\n*Modal Analysis\n*Sine Processing \n*Human Body Vibrations\n==== Acoustic analysis ====\n*Octave Analyzer\n*Sound Level Meter\n*Sound Power\n*Sound Intensity\n*Sound Quality\n*Reverberation\n*Pass-by Noise\n==== Monitoring\t ====\n*Cloud solutions\n*Machine condition monitoring\n*Structural monitoring\n==== Automation/control ====\n*Real time control frontend\n==== Telemetry ====\n*IRIG chapter 4 PCM\n*IRIG Chapter 10/iNET\n\n=== Developers ===\n\nDevelopers are able to extend Dewesoft\u2019s functionality or use some of its functions in an application of their own using several different intercas described below.\n\n==== Extending Dewesoft ====\n\nDewesoft software offers so-called plug-in technology which can be used to extend the software in several ways:\nUse the C++ script to simplify complicated formulas and create custom math modules\nUse custom plugins to add support for third-party devices, protocols or implement special math processing routines inside Dewesoft with a custom GUI\nCreate custom visual controls and displays to visualize data the way you want\nCreate custom data export functions to export data into any file format\n\nIn the past, software extension was only possible with plugins written in Delphi but Dewesoft has moved to C++ which is more commonly used compared to Delphi. The same plugin interface is also used internally by Dewesoft developers.\n\nA key functionality that became available in 2018 is the C++ Script, which allows users to write code within Dewesoft and compile it directly within the UI, without external editors. This makes it very convenient and efficient for small tasks and makes the tool especially attractive to engineers who aren\u2019t programmers by trait.\n\n==== Automation or embedding Dewesoft ====\n\nDewesoft can be used as a backend to a different program by using the following functionalities:\n\nUsing the DCOM interface the Dewesoft X software can be controlled by an external application\nDewesoft NET is able to send and receive data as well as commands over the TCP/IP protocol\nThe DWDataReader API can be used to implement support for reading Dewesoft\u2019s data file format in any data analysis tool\nBoth DCOM and NET allow custom applications to control Dewesoft to some extent and gather its data online while the DWDataReader API gives programmers access to Dewesoft\u2019s proprietary file structure. \n\n== Licensing policy ==\n\nThe software can be downloaded directly from Dewesoft\u2019s webpage and used without a license in simulation mode. A license is only required when acquiring and storing data from a physical device. Dewesoft provides a complimentary Professional license with the purchase of any Dewesoft instrument, which unlocks a broad functionality set within the software, ranging from standard mathematical analysis, visualization, sequencing and exporting data to a multitude of formats. All of the functionality is specified in Dewesoft\u2019s feature matrix. The license itself is embedded in the instrument, allowing it to be used on any PC without the need to manually transfer a license file or key.\n\nDewesoft X is completely free in analysis mode. This means once a user has stored the data he can move it to any PC, where it can be opened and analyzed without a license by a different user.\n\nDewesoft licenses do not expire and guarantee free future upgrades. Therefore, a user who purchased a Dewesoft license during the time of Dewesoft 7.0 can still use the same license with the currently released Dewesoft X3.\n\n=== Bundles, options ===\n\nDewesoft offers additional, application or protocol-specific modules that can be purchased on top of the Professional license as a one time fee. These modules are typically used for detailed analysis in a certain application (Rotor Balancer, Brake Noise, Sound Quality) or provide the means to acquire and store data from a third-party device or protocol (Ethernet Receiver, OxTS, SerialCom).\n \nOptions that are often used together as part of overarching applications are also grouped together as bundles and offered at discounted prices. For example, the Rotating Machinery Analyzer bundle includes the following options: FFT analyzer (advanced), Order tracking, Rotational and torsional vibration, Rotor balancer.\n\nIn order for users to test the purchasable functionalities on actual data, Dewesoft offers an evaluation license that unlocks the software completely for the duration of 30 days. The evaluation license can be requested using the following form.\n\n[[Category:Data analysis software]]\n[[Category:C++ software]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Notability|Products|date=April 2020}}\n{{Advert|date=April 2020}}\n{{COI|date=April 2020}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=April 2020}}\n}}\nDewesoft X is a software tool developed by Dewesoft d.o.o. with a primary focus on data recording and data analysis. It is an accompanying product to instruments from Dewesoft company. The latest version of the software is Dewesoft X3, released in October 2017.\n\n{{Infobox software\n| name = Dewesoft X\n| logo = <!-- Image name is enough. -->\n| logo alt = \n| logo caption = \n| screenshot = <!-- Image name is enough. -->\n| screenshot size =\n| screenshot alt = \n| caption = \n| collapsible = <!-- Any text here will collapse the screenshot. -->\n| author = \n| developer = Dewesoft d.o.o.\n| released = {{Start date and age|2001|df=yes}}\n| discontinued = <!-- Set to yes if software is discontinued, otherwise omit. -->\n| ver layout = <!-- simple (default) or stacked -->\n| latest release version = Dewesoft X3 SP11\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2020|03|df=yes}}\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|df=yes/no}} -->\n| repo = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| programming language = Delphi, C++\n| engine = <!-- or engines -->\n| operating system = Windows 7 or later\n| platform = x86-64\n| included with = \n| size = \n| language = \n| language count = <!-- Number only -->\n| language footnote = \n| genre = \nData acquisition, instrument control, test automation, analysis and signal processing, industrial control\n| license = Proprietary\n| alexa = \n| website = {{URL|https://dewesoft.com/products/daq-software/dewesoft-x/}}\n| standard = \n| AsOf = \n}}\n\n== Version history ==\n\nThe first version of the software is Dewesoft 5.0, released in 2001 and patented in 2002 at the USA and EU patent office for the capability of synchronized presentation of all acquired and mathematically transformed signals on a personal computer (PC). \n\nIn 2003 Dewesoft 6.0 was released, adding essential features suited for automotive, telemetry and power measurements and power analysis.\n\nDewesoft 7.0 data acquisition software was launched in 2008 with a completely overhauled graphical user interface and new capabilities.\n\nThe company changed the software\u2019s naming convention with the release of Dewesoft X in 2012. With this version of the software, Dewesoft for the first time completely abandoned support for 3rd party analog DAQ hardware and exclusively supported Dewesoft DAQ hardware. It was also no longer commercially available but was instead given to customers free of charge as an application for acquired data acquisition hardware with lifetime free upgrades.\n\nDewesoft X2 was released in 2015 and brought significant performance improvements, with calculations being executed up to 4 times faster and graphics being drawn up to 10 times faster than in Dewesoft X, due to them being executed in parallel. \n\nIn 2017 Dewesoft X3 was officially launched with its main improvement being the availability in a 64-bit version. As of February 2019, Dewesoft X3 SP10 is the latest stable build of Dewesoft X3.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name-version!! Date\n|-\n| Dewesoft 5.0 || 2001\n|-\n| Dewesoft 6.0 || 2003\n|-\n| Dewesoft 7.0 || 2008\n|-\n| Dewesoft X || 2012\n|-\n| Dewesoft X2 || 2015\n|-\n| Dewesoft X3 || 2017\n|}\n\n=== Available versions ===\n\nDewesoft X3 is always available in three versions, release, release candidate and development as part of a branching strategy to clear as many bugs as possible before deploying the software in critical operations. \n\nThe release cycle usually lasts about 2 to 3 months, after which point the versions get shifted, the release candidate branch becomes the new release branch, the development branch becomes the new release candidate branch and a new development branch is created.\n\nThe roles of the branches are as follows:\n\n*Release: the release branch is the most recent stable release version which should be used for real measurements. The version itself does not change unless a critical issue is discovered in it, at which point a patch of the release branch is released. \n\n*Release candidate: the release candidate branch contains the fixes for bugs that have been discovered in the release branch, but are not critical to the measurement process. It is updated regularly and will sometimes also include minor features.\n\n*Development: all bug fixes from the release candidate branch are also applied to the development branch, which is mostly used for adding new features. This means that all new functionality passes through an approximately 4-month long release cycle that helps discover and remove issues before deployment.\n\n[[File:X3 screen.png| thumb |Sreenshot of Dewesoft X3]]\n\n== Functionality ==\n\nDewesoft\u2019s primary objective is to be a one software solution for all applications. The current scope of functionality covers a wide range of automotive, power analysis, NVH, aerospace, industrial and civil engineering applications. At the same time, the software needs to be as easy to use as possible, allowing users to set up and perform simple measurements in a short time.\n\nThe key that allows Dewesoft to execute both effectively is that it is channel based with a modular infrastructure. All data that comes into the software (via Dewesoft hardware or otherwise) becomes a Dewesoft channel and is treated as such. Channels have basic properties (name, color, unit), can be scaled, visualized, used in other modules (statistics, filters, FFT) or exported. \n\nThe modular infrastructure means that users only see the core applications of the software, while other, more application specific parts are hidden and can be added at any time. The modules usually get data using channel inputs and they produce new channels as results. For example, the Power analysis module takes voltage and current channel as inputs and produces the calculated power, energy and THD channels.\n